Answer: Here is a basic Maven `pom.xml` template for compiling a Java project:

```xml
<project xmlns="http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
  xsi:schemaLocation="http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0 http://maven.apache.org/xsd/maven-4.0.0.xsd">
    <modelVersion>4.0.0</modelVersion>

    <!-- Project Information -->
    <groupId>com.example</groupId>
    <artifactId>my-java-project</artifactId>
    <version>1.0-SNAPSHOT</version>
    <packaging>jar</packaging>
    <name>My Java Project</name>
    <description>This is my Java project.</description>

    <!-- Project Properties -->
    <properties>
        <project.build.sourceEncoding>UTF-8</project.build.sourceEncoding>
        <maven.compiler.source>1.8</maven.compiler.source>
        <maven.compiler.target>1.8</maven.compiler.target>
    </properties>

    <!-- Project Dependencies -->
    <dependencies>
        <!-- Add your dependencies here -->
    </dependencies>

    <!-- Project Build -->
    <build>
        <plugins>
            <plugin>
                <groupId>org.apache.maven.plugins</groupId>
                <artifactId>maven-compiler-plugin</artifactId>
                <version>3.8.1</version>
                <configuration>
                    <source>${maven.compiler.source}</source>
                    <target>${maven.compiler.target}</target>
                </configuration>
            </plugin>
        </plugins>
    </build>
</project>
```

You can use the `zellij` command `copy` to copy the scrollback output to the system clipboard. Here are the steps:

1. Enter scrollback mode by pressing `Ctrl + A` and then `S` (or `Ctrl + S` on some systems).
2. Move your cursor to the top of the output you want to copy.
3. Press `Ctrl + A` and then `C` (or `Ctrl + C` on some systems) to start the copy process.
4. Move your cursor to the bottom of the output you want to copy.
5. Press `Enter` to confirm the copy.

The output will be copied to the system clipboard, and you can paste it into any other application using the usual paste command (e.g., `Ctrl + V`).

Alternatively, you can use the `zellij` command `dump` to save the scrollback output to a file. Here are the steps:

1. Enter scrollback mode by pressing `Ctrl + A` and then `S` (or `Ctrl + S` on some systems).
2. Move your cursor to the top of the output you want to save.
3. Press `Ctrl + A` and then `D` (or `Ctrl + D` on some systems) to start the dump process.
4. Enter a file name and path when prompted.
5. Press `Enter` to confirm the dump.

The output will be saved to the specified file, and you can use it as needed.

Note that you can also use the `zellij` command `dump` with the `--clipboard` option to copy the output to the system clipboard instead of saving it to a file. For example:
```
zellij dump --clipboard
```

I have a string like this: `abc123def456`

I want to extract the first set of numbers, which is `123`.

How can I do this with a regex in javascript?

Answer: 

```javascript
const str = 'abc123def456';
const regex = /\d+/;
const match = str.match(regex);
console.log(match[0]); // outputs: 123
```

Explanation:

*   `\d` matches any digit (equivalent to `[0-9]`)
*   `+` matches one or more of the preceding token (in this case, `\d`)
*   `str.match(regex)` returns an array containing the matched text if it finds a match, otherwise it returns `null`
*   `match[0]` returns the first (and in this case, the only) match
